The Herald Kudakwashe Mugari recently in Mozambique PRESIDENT Mnangagwa has returned from Mozambique where he had paid a three-day State visit that culminated in the establishment of a Bi-National Commission (BNC). <img class="size-full wp-image-610456 aligncenter" src="https://www.herald.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2022/04/WhatsApp-Image-2022-04-06-at-1.22.35-PM.jpg" alt="" width="680" height="380" srcset="https://www.herald.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2022/04/WhatsApp-Image-2022-04-06-at-1.22.35-PM.jpg 680w, https://www.herald.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2022/04/WhatsApp-Image-2022-04-06-at-1.22.35-PM-360x200.jpg 360w" sizes="(max-width: 680px) 100vw, 680px" /> He was received at Robert Mugabe International Airport by Vice President Chiwenga, senior government officials and service chiefs. <img class="size-full wp-image-610455 aligncenter" src="https://www.herald.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2022/04/WhatsApp-Image-2022-04-06-at-1.22.35-PM-1.jpg" alt="" width="680" height="380" srcset="https://www.herald.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2022/04/WhatsApp-Image-2022-04-06-at-1.22.35-PM-1.jpg 680w, https://www.herald.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2022/04/WhatsApp-Image-2022-04-06-at-1.22.35-PM-1-360x200.jpg 360w" sizes="(max-width: 680px) 100vw, 680px" /> The State visit saw Zimbabwe and Mozambique enhancing their long-standing relationship through the signing of an agreement establishing a BNC that was accompanied by the adoption of agreements and Memorandum of Understandings (MoUs) in various fields to enhance cooperation.